Part 1: Classes & Object-Oriented JavaScript
A Class is an extensible blueprint layout template used to define the structural properties and functional data rules of a targeted entity model before spawning active copies into system memory [00:01:49].

The Blueprint Analogy: An architect drafting structural floor plans on a sketch pad is a Class [00:01:03]. Walking into the neighborhood and spending capital to physically build the house yields an Object instance [00:01:23].

A. The Core Structural Components [00:02:49]
A class acts as a consolidated data storage container wrapping two essential components:

State (Properties / Data Members): Variables that hold details about the entity (e.g., age, height) [00:02:59].

Behavior (Methods / Member Functions): Functional operations the entity can execute (e.g., walking(), running()) [00:03:06].

B. Syntactic Blueprint Layout
JavaScript
class Human {
    // 1. Properties (Public fields by default) [00:07:09]
    age = 13;
    height = 180;
    
    // 2. Private Field (Prefix with a '#' symbol) [00:07:46]
    #weight = 80; `[00:05:07]`

    // 3. The Constructor Function [00:13:22]
    constructor(newAge, newHeight, newWeight) { `[00:13:54]`
        this.age = newAge;       // 'this' targets the active object context [00:09:11]
        this.height = newHeight;
        this.#weight = newWeight;
    }

    // 4. Methods / Behavior [00:04:57]
    walking() {
        console.log(`I am walking. My private weight is: ${this.#weight}`); `[00:08:43]`
    }
}

// Spawning an active Object instance using the 'new' keyword [00:05:58]
const personObj = new Human(25, 190, 75); `[00:14:36]`
personObj.walking(); // Invoking member methods using the '.' dot operator [00:04:05]
C. Access Modifiers: Public vs. Private [00:07:09]
Public Fields: Default property bindings. They are accessible anywhere inside or outside the enclosing class boundary [00:07:14].

Private Fields (#): Variables prefixed with # can only be accessed within the exact class block scopes [00:07:24]. Attempting to read personObj.#weight from the outside triggers a raw SyntaxError compilation crash [00:08:10].

D. Getters and Setters (get & set) [00:10:02]
To safely inspect or modify private class states from external script locations, use Getters and Setters [00:10:45].

JavaScript
class Human {
    #weight = 80;

    // Getter Method (Fetches private records cleanly) [00:10:32]
    get fetchWeight() {
        return this.#weight; `[00:11:11]`
    }

    // Setter Method (Applies structural updates with validation guards) [00:10:45]
    set modifyWeight(val) {
        if (val > 0) this.#weight = val; // Enforces data safety rules [00:11:43]
    }
}

const user = new Human();
user.modifyWeight = 85;      // Executes the setter like a plain property update [00:12:04]
console.log(user.fetchWeight); // Runs the getter. Outputs: 85 [00:15:53]
Benefits: They provide semantic code clarity, ensure robust data protection through integrated entry validation checks, and enable strict Encapsulation packaging boundaries [00:12:57].

Part 2: Default Function Parameters
Default Parameters allow you to pre-initialize function parameters with fallback values if no arguments are passed during invocation, or if an explicit undefined tag is detected [00:16:54].

A. The 7 Core Behavioral Variations
Variation 1: Baseline Default Primitives [00:19:06]
JavaScript
const sayName = (myName = "Prabhu Deva") => { `[00:19:11]`
    console.log(`My name is ${myName}`);
};
sayName();         // Outputs: "My name is Prabhu Deva" (Fallback applied) [00:19:19]
sayName("Babbar"); // Outputs: "My name is Babbar" (Argument used) [00:19:24]
Variation 2: Multi-Parameter Fallbacks [00:19:41]
JavaScript
const greetUser = (fName = "Uday", lName = "Singh") => { `[00:20:27]`
    console.log(`Hello, ${fName} ${lName}`);
};
greetUser("Love"); // Outputs: "Hello, Love Singh" [00:20:47]
Variation 3: Inter-Parameter Dependencies [00:20:57]
A trailing default parameter can safely inherit, calculate, or read from previous parameters listed to its left [00:21:53].

JavaScript
const processName = (fName, lName = fName.toUpperCase()) => { `[00:21:10]`
    console.log(`${fName} ${lName}`);
};
processName("Love"); // Outputs: "Love LOVE" [00:21:57]
Variation 4: Object Reference Types [00:22:27]
You can assign complete default object configurations inside parameter slots [00:23:43].

JavaScript
const initProfile = (value = { age: 15, weight: 90 }) => { `[00:23:43]`
    console.log(value.age);
};
initProfile(); // Outputs: 15 [00:24:05]
Variation 5: Array Reference Types [00:24:13]
JavaScript
const printList = (list = ["Love", "Rahul", "Kunal"]) => { `[00:24:24]`
    console.log(list);
};
printList(); // Outputs: ["Love", "Rahul", "Kunal"] [00:24:37]
Variation 6: The null vs. undefined Trap [00:24:53]
Passing null tells the engine you are intentionally providing an empty value. JavaScript will accept this literal value and skip the default parameter fallback entirely [00:25:50].

Passing undefined signals that no data is present. The engine steps in and overrides it with your configured default fallback value [00:26:01].

JavaScript
const showData = (val = "Rahul") => console.log(val); `[00:25:05]`

showData(null);      // Outputs: null [00:25:23]
showData(undefined); // Outputs: "Rahul" (Fallback triggered) [00:25:41]
Variation 7: Functions as Default Parameters [00:26:26]
You can use a function call statement as a default parameter fallback value. It will only execute if that specific argument is missing during invocation [00:28:19].

JavaScript
const getAgeValue = () => 190; `[00:26:41]`

const printUser = (name = "Love", age = getAgeValue()) => { `[00:28:09]`
    console.log(`${name} ${age}`);
};
printUser(); // Outputs: "Love 190" [00:28:23]